# Architecture

When generating or suggesting code in this repository, follow these principles.

## Architecture

Prefer a clean, testable Laravel architecture.

Structure logic in layers:

Controller → Request Validation → Service Layer → Models / Persistence

Controllers should remain thin and only handle:
	•	request validation
	•	authorization
	•	delegating to services
	•	returning responses

Business logic should live in dedicated service classes.

Example:

app/Services/AttendanceService.php

Avoid placing complex business logic in controllers or models.

⸻

## Directory Structure

Follow a RESTful approach with invokable controllers. One controller per action, one form request per write action.

### Backend

**Controllers** — `app/Http/Controllers/<Resource>/`

Use invokable controllers, one per REST action:

| Action | Controller | Route | Purpose |
|--------|------------|-------|---------|
| index | `UserIndexController` | GET /users | List resources |
| create | `UserCreateController` | GET /users/create | Show create form |
| store | `UserStoreController` | POST /users | Persist new resource |
| show | `UserShowController` | GET /users/{id} | Show single resource |
| edit | `UserEditController` | GET /users/{id}/edit | Show edit form |
| update | `UserUpdateController` | PUT/PATCH /users/{id} | Update resource |
| destroy | `UserDestroyController` | DELETE /users/{id} | Delete resource |

**Form Requests** — `app/Http/Requests/<Resource>/`

- `UserStoreRequest` — validation for store
- `UserUpdateRequest` — validation for update

**Services** — `app/Services/`

- `UserService` with methods: `index()`, `storeUser()`, `show()`, `updateUser()`, `destroyUser()`
- Read actions (create, edit) may use the service for shared data or be handled directly in the controller if trivial

**Example structure for User resource:**

```
app/
├── Http/
│   ├── Controllers/
│   │   └── User/
│   │       ├── UserIndexController.php
│   │       ├── UserCreateController.php
│   │       ├── UserStoreController.php
│   │       ├── UserShowController.php
│   │       ├── UserEditController.php
│   │       ├── UserUpdateController.php
│   │       └── UserDestroyController.php
│   └── Requests/
│       └── User/
│           ├── UserStoreRequest.php
│           └── UserUpdateRequest.php
├── Policies/
│   └── UserPolicy.php
├── Services/
│   └── UserService.php
└── Models/
    └── User.php
```

**Routes** — Map each action to its invokable controller explicitly (e.g. `Route::get('/users', UserIndexController::class)`). `Route::resource()` expects a single controller, so use explicit routes for this structure.

### Frontend

**Pages** — `resources/js/Pages/<Resource>/`

Mirror the REST actions with Vue page components:

| Action | Page | Rendered for |
|--------|------|--------------|
| index | `Index.vue` | List view |
| create | `Create.vue` | Create form |
| show | `Show.vue` | Single resource view |
| edit | `Edit.vue` | Edit form |

**Example structure for User resource:**

```
resources/js/Pages/
└── User/
    ├── Index.vue
    ├── Create.vue
    ├── Show.vue
    └── Edit.vue
```

Use this RESTful structure wherever a resource has CRUD operations. Deviate only when an action is not a standard resource operation (e.g. custom actions like `UserRestoreController`).

⸻

## Validation

Always use Laravel Form Requests for validation.

Naming: `<Resource>StoreRequest` for create, `<Resource>UpdateRequest` for update.

Examples:

- `UserStoreRequest`, `UserUpdateRequest`
- `AttendanceSessionStoreRequest`, `AttendanceSessionUpdateRequest`

Validation should include:
	•	type safety
	•	required fields
	•	relational integrity where possible

Prefer explicit validation rules over implicit assumptions.

⸻

## Authorization

Use Laravel Policies or Gates where appropriate.

Examples:
	•	Only a teacher assigned to a classroom can record attendance
	•	Only authorized users may modify attendance sessions

Never rely solely on frontend restrictions.

⸻

## Database Integrity

Enforce correctness at the database level when possible.

Examples:
	•	unique(classroom_id, date) for attendance sessions
	•	foreign keys for relationships

Use transactions for operations that modify multiple records.

Example:

DB::transaction(function () {
// atomic operations
});

⸻

## Domain Modeling

Prefer explicit domain models over generic data structures.

Example entities:
	•	School
	•	Classroom
	•	Student
	•	Teacher
	•	AttendanceSession
	•	AttendanceRecord

AttendanceSession represents attendance for a classroom on a specific date.

AttendanceRecord represents a student’s attendance status within that session.

⸻

## Observability

Code should be observable.

Include:
	•	structured logging
	•	meaningful log events
	•	error handling

Example events to log:

attendance.session.created
attendance.session.failed
attendance.records.saved

Avoid silent failures.

⸻

## Security

Follow secure defaults.

Include:
	•	authentication
	•	authorization
	•	input validation
	•	CSRF protection
	•	rate limiting where appropriate

Never trust client input.

⸻

## Simplicity

Prefer simple, maintainable solutions over complex architecture.

Avoid introducing:
	•	microservices
	•	event sourcing
	•	CQRS
	•	unnecessary abstraction

A clean Laravel monolith is preferred.

⸻

## Testability

Code should be easily testable.

Prefer:
	•	dependency injection
	•	service classes
	•	pure methods where possible

Where practical, suggest PHPUnit tests such as:

AttendanceSessionTest

Example tests:
	•	teacher_can_create_attendance_session
	•	cannot_create_duplicate_session_for_same_class_and_date
	•	teacher_can_record_student_attendance

⸻

## Performance

Avoid obvious inefficiencies such as:
	•	N+1 queries
	•	unnecessary database calls
	•	repeated queries inside loops

Prefer eager loading where appropriate.

⸻

## Communication

When generating code, assume it will be reviewed in a pull request.

Produce code that is:
	•	readable
	•	well structured
	•	easy for other developers to understand and extend.

## Domain Events

Use Laravel events to represent important domain actions.

Examples:
	•	AttendanceSessionCreated
	•	AttendanceRecorded
	•	StudentMarkedAbsent

Events should represent meaningful business events.

Dispatch events from the service layer after successful database operations.

Example:

AttendanceSessionCreated::dispatch($session);

⸻

## Event Listeners

Listeners should handle side effects such as:
	•	logging
	•	metrics
	•	notifications
	•	integrations

Listeners must not contain core business logic.

Prefer small single-responsibility listeners.

Example listeners:

LogAttendanceSessionCreated
PublishAttendanceMetrics
NotifySchoolSystem

## Jobs and Queue Architecture

When generating background processing logic, follow these principles.

When to Use Jobs

Use Laravel Jobs for work that is:
	•	slow
	•	external
	•	non-critical to the request lifecycle
	•	retryable

Examples include:
	•	sending notifications
	•	integrating with external systems
	•	generating reports
	•	background processing tasks

Avoid using jobs for very small or synchronous operations such as simple logging or small database updates.

⸻

## Relationship Between Events, Listeners, and Jobs

Follow this hierarchy:

Controller → Service → Domain Event → Listener → Job (if required)

Domain events represent important business actions.

Listeners should respond to events and may dispatch jobs for longer-running work.

Example:

AttendanceRecorded event
→ SendAbsenceNotifications listener
→ Dispatch SendParentNotification job

Listeners should remain small and focused.
